WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:06.880
Madrid, is home to some of the most fascinating&nbsp;
buildings and public spaces in Europe.

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:10.800
Yet despite its monumental&nbsp;
appearance and cultural richness,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:17.280
Madrid is actually a surprisingly young&nbsp;
city compared to Rome, Paris or London.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:21.760
Unlike many European capitals,&nbsp;
Madrid doesn’t have a Roman past.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:28.240
There are no great Roman ruins, no monumental&nbsp;
cathedral inherited from the Middle Ages.

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:39.440
In fact, the rise of Madrid began&nbsp;
relatively late, during the Renaissance.

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:43.760
In the 16th century, when Spain was&nbsp;
flourishing as a prosperous empire,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:46.720
expanding its civilization in the New World,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.960
Madrid—its present-day capital—was nothing but&nbsp;
a small fortified town with little importance.

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:57.200
During the Middle Ages, the king and the&nbsp;
court did not rule from a single city,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:02.560
but frequently moved from one city to&nbsp;
another according to political needs and war.

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:08.880
Powerful historic cities like Toledo,&nbsp;
Burgos, and León competed for prominence.

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:15.840
In 1561, King Philip II decreed that Madrid&nbsp;
was to be given the status of única corte,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:19.360
with the royal chancellery&nbsp;
transferred from Toledo.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:26.080
This insignificant town was chosen as the royal&nbsp;
seat for two main reasons: its location near&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:31.520
the geometric center of the Peninsula, and the&nbsp;
political need to consolidate the unification&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:37.600
of Spain by removing the seat of government from&nbsp;
otherwise jealously competing historic cities.

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:41.840
Within a few decades, the city’s&nbsp;
urban area grew significantly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:47.360
developing an organic pattern in which&nbsp;
streets radiated from medieval nuclei.

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:53.680
The clearest example of this, is Puerta del&nbsp;
Sol—the Gate of the Sun—which used to be a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.680 --> 00:02:01.040
gate to the old fortified town, and as the city&nbsp;
grew, it became a central space for commerce.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:07.200
Although it looks very different today, with the&nbsp;
monumental Post Office dominating the square,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:16.320
it still preserves its medieval layout of streets&nbsp;
radiating outward from the center of the city.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:20.240
Calle Mayor was a street&nbsp;
that crossed the entire city,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:26.800
stretching from the Alcázar—the king’s&nbsp;
residence—to Puerta del Sol, and beyond.

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:32.160
Along this street, were situated noble&nbsp;
palaces, taverns, and important medieval&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:37.360
squares, including Plaza de la&nbsp;
Villa—home to the old City Hall.

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:40.320
There were other important&nbsp;
squares in the city such as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:44.720
Plaza de las Descalzas and Plaza de la Paja.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:47.680
However, Plaza de la Villa is the only one that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:53.600
still has its medieval form with&nbsp;
most of its original buildings.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:57.040
For Madrid, the transitional&nbsp;
element between the Middle Ages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:04.800
and the Renaissance in terms of urbanism,&nbsp;
is the Plaza Mayor—the main central square.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:09.840
Plaza Mayor was originally a confluence&nbsp;
of roads outside the medieval city walls,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:15.520
known as Plaza del Arrabal, the town’s market&nbsp;
where commercial activities took place.

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:20.720
Plaza del Arrabal had an open, irregular&nbsp;
form, but with the rapid growth of the city’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:25.360
population that followed the establishment&nbsp;
of the court in Madrid, it was considered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:32.240
necessary to enlarge the plaza into a new&nbsp;
square worthy of the seat of the royal court.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:36.160
The construction of Plaza Mayor was commenced in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:41.920
1617 following the design of&nbsp;
architect Juan Gómez de Mora.

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:46.320
A perfect confinement is achieved in&nbsp;
the new heart of the city by carving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:52.320
a perfect rectangular space out&nbsp;
of the medieval urban fabric.

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:57.040
At the time, an extensive Baroque system&nbsp;
of streets connecting public spaces was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.040 --> 00:04:03.120
being developed in many European cities, but&nbsp;
in Spain this concept was rarely adopted.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:09.120
Instead, major planned public spaces such as&nbsp;
Plaza Mayor remained completely isolated from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:14.400
the city’s main streets, so that nothing would&nbsp;
disturb their sense of enclosed space intended&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:22.720
for public gathering—possibly a feature inherited&nbsp;
from the courtyards of medieval mosques in Spain.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:27.440
Plaza Mayor became the principal stage&nbsp;
for public spectacles, being able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:34.480
accommodate more than 50,000 people, some&nbsp;
4,000 of them in the enclosing buildings.

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:39.280
Uniquely Spanish urban activities that&nbsp;
developed in the Plaza Mayor included&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:44.080
bullfighting on horseback—a tradition&nbsp;
that had already consolidated in Spain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.080 --> 00:04:51.440
in the previous century, and from which&nbsp;
later evolved the special-purpose plaza&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:55.920
de toros—and autos de fe—solemn&nbsp;
events by the Inquisition where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.920 --> 00:05:06.320
heretics were judged and executed—as well&nbsp;
as religious celebrations such as Easter.

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:08.880
Serving as the backdrop for public ceremonies,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:16.800
Casa de la Panadería was the chief building of the&nbsp;
square, recognizable by its steepled clock towers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:25.920
its arcade on the base, and by&nbsp;
the later frescoes on its facade.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:28.560
The building functioned as&nbsp;
a bread shop on the ground&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:34.080
floor and housed the royal box on the first floor.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:38.560
Something I like about Plaza mayor is&nbsp;
the perspectives created within the main&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:43.840
entrances to the precinct— Because the square&nbsp;
is embedded within an organic medieval fabric,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:48.480
its access points are not coming in&nbsp;
orthogonally, but approach at oblique angles.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:50.320
Yet all of them converge visually toward the&nbsp;
center—so you can be standing all the way across&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.320 --> 00:06:04.640
the street over there, and you’ll always&nbsp;
see the central statue framed by the arch.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:11.280
Plazas Mayores—main central squares—were the&nbsp;
outstanding contribution of Spain to European&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:16.720
urbanism, and Madrid’s Plaza Mayor,&nbsp;
became the model of plazas mayores&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:23.280
that would be exported into all the Spanish&nbsp;
cities including those in the New World.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:28.880
After Madrid became the permanent seat of the&nbsp;
court, Philip II heavily modified the Moorish&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:35.280
citadel that had stood on the site since the 9th&nbsp;
century, converting it into the Real Alcázar de&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:42.160
Madrid, which in its final phase—after successive&nbsp;
additions made by later monarchs—resulted in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:50.000
hybrid of medieval and Renaissance architecture: a&nbsp;
great mass dominating the western edge of Madrid.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:54.560
Its plan preserved the footprint&nbsp;
of the Moorish citadel, adapted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:59.440
to the border of the cliff on which&nbsp;
it stood, above the river Manzanares.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:02.960
The building was organized&nbsp;
around two central courtyards,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:05.520
separated by the royal chapel in the middle.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:13.360
The main facade faced a large forecourt,&nbsp;
also inherited from the old citadel.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:16.960
This elevation displayed a&nbsp;
clear Renaissance character,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:23.920
with a symmetrical composition of lateral towers&nbsp;
and a central body framing the main entrance.

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:30.160
Columns articulating the two upper levels framed&nbsp;
each window, and paired columns were featured&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:35.520
in the central body with a protruding&nbsp;
gable bearing the royal coat of arms.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:38.480
Those steepled towers that defined its silhouette,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:42.560
are very characteristic of&nbsp;
Madrid’s 17th century architecture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:49.520
and you can still see them in many buildings&nbsp;
and churches that survive from that time.

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:54.400
On Christmas Eve 1734, a&nbsp;
fire destroyed the Alcázar,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.400 --> 00:08:02.480
and four years later construction began on the&nbsp;
Palacio Real, the Royal Palace that we see today.

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:08.160
For this new residence, King Philip V, who&nbsp;
had been born and raised at Versailles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:13.920
wanted a more modern and monumental palace, so&nbsp;
he commissioned the Italian Baroque architect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:19.840
Filippo Juvarra to design the building in the&nbsp;
style of the great European palaces of the time.

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:25.280
Juvarra planned a huge three-court complex,&nbsp;
but after his death, his successor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:33.200
Giovanni Battista Sacchetti, changed the&nbsp;
plans and constructed a single-court block.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:37.920
The facade features columns of giant&nbsp;
order over a rusticated ground floor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:46.640
with protruding sections at the corners and&nbsp;
center, and the courtyard is composed of an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:52.960
arcade of two tiers with a recessed third&nbsp;
level to reduce the impact of the scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:58.080
thus achieving a well-lit&nbsp;
space of excellent proportions.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:04.960
Sacchetti’s design is heavily influenced&nbsp;
by Bernini’s unrealized design for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:12.560
the Louvre in Paris, which features&nbsp;
the exact same layout and elements.

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:18.000
On the opposite side of the Palacio&nbsp;
Real you can see the Almudena Cathedral,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:24.080
but don’t be fooled by the Neoclassical appearance&nbsp;
of its exterior, this is a 20th century building.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:27.600
For most of its history,&nbsp;
Madrid didn’t have a Cathedral,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:32.560
as the diocese of the region was&nbsp;
located in the city of Toledo,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:37.200
so really the closest thing to a cathedral that&nbsp;
Madrid ever had was the Colegiata de San Isidro,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:41.600
a beautiful baroque church located&nbsp;
just a few blocks from here.

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:52.480
This church, though beautiful, is just an eclectic&nbsp;
result of much later architectural ambitions.

00:09:52.480 --> 00:09:58.160
In the second half of the 18th century, as the&nbsp;
spirit of the Enlightenment spread across Europe,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:03.200
there was a growing ambition to put Spain at&nbsp;
the level of other European powers in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:09.760
scientific advancement, so, on the outskirts&nbsp;
of the city was planned the Salón del Prado,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:15.280
a great tree-lined avenue designed to&nbsp;
integrate art, science, and nature,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:22.240
through three major architectural projects: an&nbsp;
astronomical observatory, a botanical garden,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:27.120
and a royal museum—today&nbsp;
the famous Museo del Prado.

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:33.665
These three projects were commissioned to one of&nbsp;
the most illustrious architects of the time, Juan&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.665 --> 00:10:40.640
de Villanueva, who refined and consolidated in&nbsp;
Spain the Neoclassical language of architecture.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:46.560
For the Museo del Prado, Villanueva envisioned a&nbsp;
building that combined the functions of a Natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:53.120
History Museum and a Temple of Science&nbsp;
intended to house learned societies.

00:10:53.120 --> 00:11:00.960
A central block and two vast pavilions&nbsp;
are attached by extended wings.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:04.720
The building is characterized by&nbsp;
screens of columns and arches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:07.360
and a restrained use of ornament.

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:13.520
Under Ferdinand VII the Prado was transformed&nbsp;
into a picture gallery—a use it continues to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:19.440
serve today—housing one of the finest&nbsp;
collections of paintings in the world.

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:24.960
Within the urban project of the Salón del Prado,&nbsp;
numerous landscape elements would be placed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:30.240
among them the fountains of&nbsp;
Neptune, Apollo, and Cybele.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:34.960
These helped to articulate the axis of the avenue.

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:43.040
At the western edge of the city, Philip IV&nbsp;
had built the Palacio del Buen Retiro in 1630.

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:47.840
As its name suggests, it was&nbsp;
conceived as a palace of retreat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:52.800
used as a secondary royal residence,&nbsp;
surrounded by extensive gardens.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:57.680
Palacio del Buen Retiro was seriously&nbsp;
damaged during the Napoleonic Wars,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.680 --> 00:12:01.760
and gradually fell into decline&nbsp;
over the course of the 19th century,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:05.520
until most of the complex&nbsp;
was eventually demolished.

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:10.560
Only two elements survived: the&nbsp;
Casón—the ballroom—and the Salón&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:15.200
de Reinos—a room used for diplomatic receptions.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:21.760
You can still see these two buildings today,&nbsp;
now absorbed into the urban fabric of Madrid.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:28.560
The former palace gardens, however, endured&nbsp;
and were transformed in the 19th century into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:34.560
a picturesque, Romantic landscape, enriched&nbsp;
with architectural and sculptural elements,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:43.680
before being opened to the public as a city&nbsp;
park—today known as Parque del Buen Retiro.

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:49.520
Enclosing the entire city, was the&nbsp;
Customs wall of Philip IV, built in 1625.

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:54.560
This wall was never a truly defensive&nbsp;
structure, but instead served for centuries&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.560 --> 00:13:00.320
as the administrative boundary of the city,&nbsp;
regulating goods and controlling access to Madrid.

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:07.040
The wall was demolished in the 1860s.&nbsp;
However, two of its royal gates still survive.

00:13:07.040 --> 00:13:10.800
One is the famous Puerta de Alcalá—a Neoclassical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:17.680
gate that stood on the main road leading to&nbsp;
the neighboring city of Alcalá de Henares.

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:25.120
The other is Puerta de Toledo, designed&nbsp;
in the form of a triumphal arch, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:33.520
erected to commemorate the restoration of&nbsp;
the monarchy after the Napoleonic occupation.

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:37.760
By the late 19th century, Madrid’s&nbsp;
uncontrolled population growth as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:43.600
a result of industrialization, lead to&nbsp;
overcrowding and poor sanitary conditions.

00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:48.160
So it became necessary to expand the&nbsp;
city outward in a controlled way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.160 --> 00:13:51.280
with the aim of creating a modern capital city,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:56.960
comparable to other European capitals like&nbsp;
Paris under the reforms of Napoleon III.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:02.480
So a grid expansion of the city known as&nbsp;
“ensanche” or “enlargement” was proposed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:08.560
in 1860 with straight, wide streets,&nbsp;
reinforcing the idea of light and air,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:14.400
seeking a healthy city, very different to&nbsp;
the medieval, organic fabric of the old city.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:20.080
The plan also designated spaces for housing&nbsp;
as well as spaces for parish churches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:22.880
hospitals, and other public buildings.

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:28.640
The north would comprise the high society, with&nbsp;
elegant neighborhoods like Salamanca and Chamberí.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:33.520
The east would comprise the middle classes and&nbsp;
the south the working classes and industry.

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:36.080
This segregation was not entirely intentional,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:41.040
but it reflects the social&nbsp;
structure of the 19th century.

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:43.440
The ensanche of Madrid was carried out over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:48.480
several decades, and solved many of&nbsp;
the issues that the city presented.

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:54.560
However, by the early 20th century, the&nbsp;
historic center remained dense and overcrowded,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.560 --> 00:15:00.320
so in order to modernize the old city and&nbsp;
improve its circulation, over 300 buildings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:06.480
were demolished to make way for Gran Vía, a great&nbsp;
avenue that cuts through the medieval fabric,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:12.800
planned to accommodate great hotels,&nbsp;
theaters, and commercial buildings.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:19.760
Something I think is interesting about Gran Vía,&nbsp;
is that you can see how architectural styles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:25.680
evolved as Gran Vía was being developed—in the&nbsp;
first section, Beaux Arts buildings predominate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:30.800
and as you keep walking along the avenue,&nbsp;
these gradually give way to Art Deco buildings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:30.800 --> 00:15:38.800
which had become popular by the late&nbsp;
1920s when Gran Vía was finished.

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:50.720
You can distinguish three separate&nbsp;
periods of urban unity in Madrid.

00:15:50.720 --> 00:15:56.720
When the city was established as the capital&nbsp;
in 1561, Spain was ruled by the house of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:03.200
Austrias—the Habsburg dynasty—and you clearly&nbsp;
see a characteristic Madrid style in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:11.200
architecture—sober Renaissance forms in austere&nbsp;
brick buildings with details in stone, towers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:20.160
with steeples, a Plaza Mayor, and a layout of the&nbsp;
city that organically develops as the city grows.

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:24.720
In 1700 the last king of the&nbsp;
Austrias died without an heir,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:29.120
and the French Bourbon dynasty&nbsp;
ascended to the Spanish throne.

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:33.360
The Bourbons shifted towards a very&nbsp;
French-style centralist and absolute&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:39.760
monarchy and you can see this clearly reflected in&nbsp;
the architecture—more monumental and symmetrical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:46.080
forms made entirely in stone, like the new&nbsp;
Royal Palace with an Italian Baroque style,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:52.160
other buildings featuring Italian and&nbsp;
French influences, and a more axial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:52.160 --> 00:17:00.080
urban planning like Salón del Prado, which follows&nbsp;
the new trends of European monumental urbanism.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:03.520
The third period, defined by&nbsp;
the Ensanche and the opening&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:11.440
of Gran Vía, marks the emergence&nbsp;
of the modern capital of Spain.

00:17:11.440 --> 00:17:16.400
These three layers form the&nbsp;
complex urban identity of Madrid:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:24.080
a city where organic medieval growth,&nbsp;
Baroque order, and modern planning coexist,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.080 --> 00:17:40.240
each one still legible in its streets,&nbsp;
shaping the way you experience the city today.

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:42.240
Remember that if you join as a channel member,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.240 --> 00:17:48.080
you can watch extended versions of my videos with&nbsp;
much more detailed explanations and live videos.

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:49.440
Thank you so much for watching.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:51.040
I hope you enjoyed and learned.

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:55.600
Please like this video, subscribe to my channel,&nbsp;
and I'll see you very soon in another episode.

00:17:55.600 --> 00:17:56.480
Goodbye!

